From: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sat, 31 May 2026 14:25:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] Input: rotary-encoder - debounce reports to tame contact
 bounce

The half-period state machine latches a direction from the last odd
(intermediate) gray-code state it sampled, then reports it the next
time it sees an even (stable) state. It never checks that the right
intermediate state was actually traversed. A mechanical encoder
bounces hard on every detent, and on Amlogic G12A the gpio_intc edges
arrive completely unfiltered (the controller's input glitch filter is
never programmed). Worse, on this SoC EDGE_BOTH has to be faked with
one single-edge gpio_intc channel per (line, edge) - four threaded
oneshot IRQs that each read live GPIO levels whenever they happen to
run, not the level at edge time. Feed that decoder a bounce burst and
it emits spurious even-state reports and, when a bounce momentarily
reads the opposite odd neighbour, latches and reports the wrong
direction. The symptom is scroll that mostly tracks but randomly
stutters and reverses, worsening with rotation speed.

Rate-limit the reports the way the stock Spotify kernel did: stamp
each emitted event and drop any report that lands within
debounce_interval of the previous one. A bounce burst collapses to its
first edge, and after every report the decoder ignores input long
enough for the contacts to settle before the next genuine detent is
sampled. The interval comes from the "debounce-interval" device
property (milliseconds) and defaults to 20 ms, matching stock; that
caps the report rate at 50/s, which is far above any human knob speed.

This is the symptom-relevant fix. It pairs with programming the
gpio_intc glitch filter (separate patch), which rejects sub-window
glitches at the pin without throttling legitimate fast rotation; stock
ran both, on top of a tighter two-IRQ edge-both topology than ours, so
we lean on both here too.

Signed-off-by: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Upstream-Status: Pending
---
 drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c | 20 ++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 20 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c b/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c
--- a/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c
+++ b/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c
@@ -22,9 +22,12 @@
 #include <linux/of.h>
 #include <linux/pm.h>
 #include <linux/property.h>
+#include <linux/timekeeping.h>

 #define DRV_NAME "rotary-encoder"

+#define DEFAULT_DEBOUNCE_INTERVAL 20	/* ms */
+
 enum rotary_encoder_encoding {
 	ROTENC_GRAY,
 	ROTENC_BINARY,
@@ -51,6 +54,9 @@
 	signed char dir;	/* 1 - clockwise, -1 - CCW */

 	unsigned int last_stable;
+
+	u32 debounce_interval;	/* ns */
+	u64 t_last_event;
 };

 static unsigned int rotary_encoder_get_state(struct rotary_encoder *encoder)
@@ -73,6 +79,13 @@

 static void rotary_encoder_report_event(struct rotary_encoder *encoder)
 {
+	u64 t_event = ktime_get_ns();
+
+	/* drop reports within debounce_interval of the last; collapses contact-bounce edge storms */
+	if (t_event - encoder->t_last_event < encoder->debounce_interval)
+		return;
+	encoder->t_last_event = t_event;
+
 	if (encoder->relative_axis) {
 		input_report_rel(encoder->input,
 				 encoder->axis, encoder->dir);
@@ -230,6 +243,13 @@
 	encoder->relative_axis =
 		device_property_read_bool(dev, "rotary-encoder,relative-axis");

+	err = device_property_read_u32(dev, "debounce-interval",
+				       &encoder->debounce_interval);
+	if (err)
+		encoder->debounce_interval = DEFAULT_DEBOUNCE_INTERVAL;
+	encoder->debounce_interval *= NSEC_PER_MSEC;
+	encoder->t_last_event = ktime_get_ns();
+
 	encoder->gpios = devm_gpiod_get_array(dev, NULL, GPIOD_IN);
 	if (IS_ERR(encoder->gpios))
 		return dev_err_probe(dev, PTR_ERR(encoder->gpios), "unable to get gpios\n");
